- 'Active stations' refers to monitoring locations with a status of 'active';
- 'Sounding the alarm' means the average measurement value of the pollutant exceeds its regulatory limit;
- 'Legal threshold' is the regulatory limit set for each pollutant.

- "current state of air quality" refers to the most recent average pollutant levels;
- "watchful guardians" refers to the active monitoring stations;
- "keeping an eye on the environment" refers to the monitoring activities of these stations.

- 'Top 3 pollutants' refers to the pollutants with the highest average measurement values in each city;
- 'Active monitoring stations' are stations with a status of 'active';
- The time frame for the measurements is from May 1, 2023, to May 31, 2023.

- 'Average breath of life' refers to the average value of PM2.5 measurements;
- 'Abids sanctuary' refers to the monitoring location named 'Abids';
- 'Blossoming month of May 2023' refers to the period from May 1, 2023, to May 31, 2023.

- PM2.5 refers to particulate matter with a diameter of 2.5 micrometers or less, which is a common air pollutant;
- Active status indicates that the monitoring station is currently operational and collecting data;
- More than 10 measurements ensure that the average value is based on a sufficient amount of data for reliability.

- "most crowded with pollutants" refers to the highest count of pollutants at a monitoring location;
- "average regulatory limits" are the mean values of the regulatory limits for pollutants at each location;
- "highest regulatory limits" are the maximum values of the regulatory limits for pollutants at each location.

- 'Active users' are those who have logged into the system within the last 30 days;
- 'Cumulative value' represents the total measurement of pollutants across different locations;
- 'Active monitoring locations' are those with a status marked as 'active';
- 'Recent pollutant levels' are measurements taken within the last 30 days.
